Rock music, unlike Metal, is not instrumental music for the most part. Rock music typically is arranged in strict vocal song structures like other forms of popular music. The rhythm section (rhythm guitar, bass, and percussion) is strictly rhythmic for the vocals to sing over. Keith Richards asserted that Rock ‘n’ Roll developed from Blues musicians like Chuck Berry in the early '50s directly transposing two chord Blues/Boogie rhythm riffs from piano to electric guitar and replacing shouted vocals with pop singing, hooks, and structure. Richards is probably right; Rock riffs are typically two to three chords arranged around a static center while the Blues leads are mere adornment so the vocal melody and catchy rhythms can prevail. For an example, let us have a listen to one of the more instrumentally focused Hard Rock bands:
https://youtu.be/2atkj_KWLl0

Led Zeppelin’s “Communication Breakdown” is a verse-chorus-verse song based around a fixed three chord verse Boogie riff for Robert Plant to wail and howl over like a 50s Rock ‘n’ Roller. The chorus riff is a standard Rock ‘n’ Roll Bluesy Boogie that exists to proceeds forth into the solo in the bridge before the vocal chorus repeats and the song fades out. “Communication Breakdown” like most Rock music is held back by the need to make a radio Rock song. Led Zeppelin performed much better with their more virtuosic progressive rock songs such as “Achilles Last Stand”. The guitars are structured like vocal arrangements in prior rock music while keeping the repetitive Rock feel to progress each instrument to the catchy hooks and choruses over a steady rhythm riff, bass line, and drum beat in an extended rock jam from well-practiced former studio musicians:
https://youtu.be/1t4KLOm7pO0

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Metal, even Heavy Metal based around riff pairs, in contrast is melodically structured instrumental music. Metal uses heavy, Psychedelic and Blues-based riffs based around power chords and merely repeated phrases in a longer melodic construction that is usually minor-key, modal, or chromatic. Tonal centers of Metal riffs in each composition (metal tracks are not vocally-based so therefore not songs) are not fixed but progress over the course of it. The “rhythm guitar” is therefore not a merely a rhythm instrument but in fact the lead one. Unless you're shredding, there can be no Metal without a rhythm guitar. The drum kit is enslaved to the guitars as a mere metronomic timekeeper despite whatever swing, texture, or fills the drummer flourishes the music with. If Robbing the Graveyard and Raping the Dead from Satan's Massacre is any proof, you construct Metal music simply with your amp and guitar with no bass or percussion needed at all.

For comparison, let's listen to Motörhead. They combined riff progression with chopped up minor key melodies to progress their Heavy and Speed Metal compositions forward. Listen to “Overkill”‘s thrashy metronomic pick-up beat, the shifting forward chord progressions, and the appropriately progressing leads:
https://youtu.be/ueeEEXE7Po8

Motörhead’s minimalist approach to writing music meant that they never had to budget riff; Lemmy and company always exploited the basic melody in a riff way further than they needed to in order to construct a Speed Metal track or whatever other genre they felt like playing such as the occasional crooner ballads. Despite repeating rhythms and structures, they successfully reexerted this formula artistically and commercially until Lemmy died right after the release of Bad Magic:
https://youtu.be/Zh_pk02IOnE

>Back in the day bands like AC/DC and Deep Purple were considered heavy metal.
the tropes of heavy metal didn't really get codified until the late 70s/early 80s with the New Wave of British Heavy Metal, so there's a lot of confusion and crossover in the 70s. Here are some major differences between the two genres:

*the blues: classic hard rock bands all had a huge blues influence in lyrics, vocalization, guitar chord vocabulary, drumming, and use of improvisation, among other things. some of that gets toned down during the 80s but it's still there at the core of the music. hard rock, at least when compared to metal, is more "loose", "funky" and improvisational. hard rock bands often improvise ("jam") live.
in metal, 99% of the time improvisation only occurs during designated guitar solo sections. everything else is written out ahead of time.
while both genres emphasize guitar riffs, heavy metal songs are ENTIRELY built around guitar riffs.

*drums: metal drums are not funky and instead provide a driving "four on the floor" feel.

*bass: the bass players in metal almost always double the guitar part, while in hard rock (for instance "ramble on" by led zeppelin) the bass player often plays a different, but complimentary melody line.

*ballads: ballad-type songs are common in hard rock but almost entirely absent in heavy metal. metal bands don't do romance.

*dynamics: hard rock songs often feature an ebb and flow of dynamics (loudness and softness). heavy metal songs might feature a soft intro or outro but other than that are loud and aggressive the entire time (this rule gets broken when you get into progressive metal). heavy metal music is extreme, with everything "turned up to 11": over the top vocals, virtuosic guitar shredding, merciless drumming. hard rock has more subtlety and nuance.

I love 90s ads and promos.
There's just this sense of fear and loathing in them.
They knew that the audience was:
>kids, who like weird shit because they're kids
>teens and young adults who were all high as fuck

You don't even get close to that sort of awareness in advertisement, because ceos now have such a warped perception of their audience and such a condescending "you will like this whether you like it or not" tone to their marketing now.
In the past, marketing wasn't indoctrination, it was a snake selling you an apple from the vine and people were frank about it because they realised that this was just how it was in reality.

Now it's all about pretending to be perfect and infallible. That's why you have this fucked up shit with pharma companies forcing their marketing down your throat to the point of controlling censorship now.
In the past that was just unthinkable when I was a kid.
People say it's always been like that, but I disagree. You look at ads from the 90s and people were fully frank about their nature as a snake oil salesmen in most things because that's just simply how free markets work and how we get new innovations. It's clumsy and rough. But at least it's not mere propaganda. Marketing is marketing, not propaganda. People don't understand how that is nowadays.

>>114990301
2013 was like 3 whole cultural eras away from the current one. "Indie," referring to any kind of small-scale but notable industry actually making, selling, and marketing decent music in some decent level of quantity, has been dead since 2015. That year pitchfork got bought by conde nast, the last of the new york showspaces were destroyed, and streaming replaced cd's and itunes. The last on is important because it completely gutted artist revenues from everything besides merch and live shows. No one could sell records anymore, and the entire industry kind of dried up. The next year of course a bunch of political shit happened, everything got acrimonious, and also there was the ghost ship warehouse fire which killed over 30 people. Within about 3 years people making actual music were pretty much left with no way to break through as unknown artists, or to make money from their music. Then the pandemic raped touring for 2 years. The entire music industry outside of major celebrities is really hard-up. Terrible time to be a musician. Even 10 years ago, when it was a 'hipster' scene that people shat on, it was thriving in comparision. People made fun of it but in hindsight it's much better than nothing at all except political shrieking. At least the obnoxious hipsters sometimes made actual music. Now it's almost extinct. >>114974347
Bowie has several GREAT albums. My favorite is Station To Station but I'm not married to it, I could easily listen to any of his classic-era albums and be edified.

He did have a late-career decline, like many artists do. His albums after Let's Dance tend toward the contrived. Except what he did with Tin Machine, which was excellent.

Still, anything Bowie put out from 1970-1983 is considered all-time classic rock, and rightfully so. Interesting sidenote, unlike most musicians Bowie didn't have a "sophomore slump." His first eponymous release is actually his worst album, after that he simply got better and better, consistently, until Scary Monsters. Bowie was a true artist, I would LOVE to be a musical novice just starting to explore his catalog, great memories, great music.

In speaking of having a true artist mentality, David Bowie has to be the only person I've heard of who established themselves with a popular and critically acclaimed career as a solo artist, who also proactively surrendered that position for the sake of achieving something greater as one among equals. When that happens otherwise, it almost always comes off as something done begrudgingly, especially considering how royalties and song-crediting makes adding more members a financial compromise.

This speaks to something which Bowie had that other great artists have - a strong self-awareness of one's own ego and an ability to intentionally alter it in the moment for maximal artist impact. I mean he was still the frontman and the popular music press wouldn't really accept it as anything but Bowie's backing band, but the music they put out really speaks to how much they all complimented one another. New anon jumping in.
Keep in mind Pin Ups primary motivation for being made was to get the record company off Bowie's back while he was recuperating from touring and his manager was going through financial negotiations with the company. If there was any album which Bowie could be accused of shitting out, this would be it.

Now, is it terrible for what it is, essentially just Bowie covering songs that influenced him in his glam style with no greater pretension?
IMHO It could have been significantly better with minimal investment if Bowie went with songs that complemented his glam style better. "See Emily Play" is the strongest cover IMHO, plays the feel of the original well. Meanwhile, "Shapes of Things" obliterates the original feeling with the timbre and vocal choice, and every effect tacked on takes away from the song as a whole.

So while I never have much desire to listen to it, I think calling it a competent fluff album that served a practical purpose in its time is a reasonable take.

Let's clarify things. I am the most knowledgable among you, and here's what it is regarding Bowie.

He had a classic era in which he could do no wrong, everything he put out was absolutely art of the highest integrity. That period ran from Man Who Sold The World to Let's Dance.

But Bowie was also a narcissist. He KNEW he was musically irrelevant but he DESIRED the spotlight. So he continued to put out albums after Let's Dance, which should have been his magnum opus.

Fine. Bowie is a huge, important musical icon. He was totally entitled to put out music into his middle age. We didn't HAVE TO buy it or even listen to it. Of course, we did, because it was Bowie. But it was never mandatory.

Did Bowie damage his legacy by issuing a bunch of garbage late in his career? Absolutely not. Unlike other artists, we KNOW Bowie, and we KNOW that...this...isn't his best work, it's just work.

So all is forgiven for David Bowie. Yet somehow there are absolute mouth-breathing morons on this forum trying to defend his shitty late-career output like it's their fucking job. Okay. Like, seriously, WHATEVER. But don't go acting all self-righteous and shit, dudes, we KNOW you're the dipshits.

>>114985226
I bought an alto recorder recently. So far, I spent several hours learning to play the main melody from "U. N. Owen Was Her?" (transposed for easier fingering, slowed down a bit), and I played "Hot Cross Buns" (version on Wikipedia, also transposed), which was much easier. I don't care about sharps and flats and key signatures, so I am learning everything using tabs (0 for the lowest note, 1 for the next chromatic note above it, and so on). This way the fingering is the same for C and F recorders, and it's very easy to transpose things.

I bought a method book and I'm grinding the exercises before attempting any more tunes. I annotate the exercises with tabs as I try them. I have freakishly short pinky fingers, so I have to use "piper's grip" for finger 6 to avoid pain, but I see some pros doing this on Youtube, so it can't be so bad. I also ordered a thumb rest because the recorder is shiny plastic and it gradually slips through my fingers unless I grip it ridiculously hard.

Recorder is much easier and more fun than guitar, which I've tried before and never got anywhere with.

posts.com: >I went to pick up some drums from a studio they were in, found out they needed a drummer and joined the band. They were very narrow in their musical tastes; it was all E.L.P. and Yes types of things and little else. They had a ridiculous opinion of themselves but after playing with musician the calibre of Camel I found I had to play down to their level of competence, which was very frustrating musically. I appeared in the Garden Party video and did some British dates and then in the states. There was a lot of friction between us, it all came to a head in New York supporting Todd Rundgren, and there's Fish standing at the side of the stage ranting, "we shouldn't be supporting this shit, we're ten times better than this cosmic rabbit", and I just did my nut. How dare he slag off someone the calibre of Todd Rundgren, who, quite frankly, had more talent in his pinky than the whole of Marillion, me included. Things got quite heated, and I shoved him in the chest, to be honest this was just the last day in a long line of pathetic and niggly incidents with the band. Three days later I was asked up to the managers room and fired. It was hard seeing them at number one the year after, thinking that could be me on Top of the Pops! Actually I quite liked Fish, we generally got on well together, he was the real talent within the band at that time, I think.
